1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,480
In the previous lesson, we explained what
marketing means in professional services

2
00:00:04,480 --> 00:00:07,245
and why reputation and relationships
drive revenue.

3
00:00:08,245 --> 00:00:12,048
In this lesson, we'll describe the
marketing mix and apply the seven Ps

4
00:00:12,048 --> 00:00:14,004
services model to an advisory offer.

5
00:00:15,004 --> 00:00:20,020
Every marketing decision a firm makes can
be grouped into a small set of levers.

6
00:00:20,020 --> 00:00:26,463
Traditionally, these were captured as the
four Ps: product, price, place, and

7
00:00:26,463 --> 00:00:27,311
promotion.

8
00:00:28,311 --> 00:00:30,076
Product is what the firm offers.

9
00:00:31,076 --> 00:00:32,980
Price is what it charges.

10
00:00:33,980 --> 00:00:36,256
Place is how the offer reaches the
client.

11
00:00:37,256 --> 00:00:40,089
Promotion is how the firm communicates
its value.

12
00:00:41,089 --> 00:00:44,665
These four levers were designed for
companies selling physical products.

13
00:00:44,665 --> 00:00:49,546
For an advisory firm, they capture only
part of the picture, because the product

14
00:00:49,546 --> 00:00:51,585
is a service delivered by people.

15
00:00:52,585 --> 00:00:57,842
To market services well, three further
levers are added: people, process, and

16
00:00:57,842 --> 00:00:59,087
physical evidence.

17
00:00:59,087 --> 00:01:04,381
Together with the original four, these
make up the seven Ps services mix.

18
00:01:05,381 --> 00:01:09,561
People matter because, in advisory work,
the people are the service.

19
00:01:10,561 --> 00:01:15,513
Process matters because clients judge how
an engagement is run, not just its

20
00:01:15,513 --> 00:01:16,041
outcome.

21
00:01:17,041 --> 00:01:21,076
Physical evidence matters because
intangible work needs tangible proof,

22
00:01:21,076 --> 00:01:23,728
such as credentials, case studies, and
reports.

23
00:01:24,728 --> 00:01:25,982
Think of a restaurant.

24
00:01:26,982 --> 00:01:31,618
The meal is the product, but the service,
the atmosphere, and the way each course

25
00:01:31,618 --> 00:01:33,994
arrives shape the experience just as
much.

26
00:01:33,994 --> 00:01:36,548
Professional services work the same way.

27
00:01:37,548 --> 00:01:42,407
For an advisory firm, the most powerful
levers are usually people, process, and

28
00:01:42,407 --> 00:01:45,211
physical evidence, rather than price or
place.

29
00:01:46,211 --> 00:01:51,205
A firm differentiates through the calibre
of its teams, the rigour of its methods,

30
00:01:51,205 --> 00:01:53,363
and the quality of its credentials.

31
00:01:53,363 --> 00:01:57,218
These are the levers a partner can
actually pull to win and keep work.

32
00:01:58,218 --> 00:02:01,329
For FinSage, the seven Ps reveal a blind
spot.

33
00:02:02,329 --> 00:02:06,975
The firm competes hard on its services
and fees, but pays little attention to

34
00:02:06,975 --> 00:02:09,481
how it presents its people and past work.

35
00:02:09,481 --> 00:02:14,390
Strengthening its physical evidence, such
as sharper case studies, could raise its

36
00:02:14,390 --> 00:02:16,633
win rate without changing its prices.

37
00:02:17,633 --> 00:02:20,094
Let's stop the lesson here.

38
00:02:21,094 --> 00:02:24,577
In this lesson, we first described the
classic four Ps.

39
00:02:25,577 --> 00:02:29,571
We then saw how the seven Ps extend the
mix for services.

40
00:02:30,571 --> 00:02:33,450
Finally, we applied the mix to an
advisory firm.

41
00:02:34,450 --> 00:02:38,303
In the next lesson, we'll examine the
characteristics that make services

42
00:02:38,303 --> 00:02:39,605
different from products.

